          <td align="center" height="42"> 
            <h2>MSc in Carbon Management</h2>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td valign="top" height="311"> 
            <div align="left"> 
              <p>&nbsp;</p>
              <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/23r65OpCEXw" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
              <p>&nbsp;</p>
              
              <p>With carbon management becoming increasingly central to business, 
                governments and consumers across the world Dave Reay of GHGonline.org 
                and colleagues at the University of Edinburgh launched a new <b><a href="http://www.ed.ac.uk/schools-departments/geosciences/postgraduate/masters-programme/taught-masters/msc-carbon-management">MSc 
                in Carbon Management</a></b> in 2008. Our first cohort of 38 Carbon 
                Masters graduated in 2009, having completed a great year for us 
                all, including presentations to the Scottish Parliament and the 
                launch of their own carbon consultancy called' 'Carbon Masters'.</p>
              <p>Since the inaugural year (2008-09) the programme intake has grown 
                to 30-50 Carbon Masters each year and has gone from strength to 
                strength. In December 2009 the Carbon Masters were delegates at 
                the <b><a href="http://www.business-school.ed.ac.uk/about/news-and-press-office/?a=18840">climate 
                change conference in Copenhagen</a></b> and received a standing 
                ovation for their presentations alongside the Scottish Government 
                and the British Council. </p>
              <p>In 2010 the programme won the EUSA PwC Award for 'Teaching Employable 
                Skills' and in 2015 was ranked in top 
                10 Best Masters in the World for 'Sustainable Development 
                and Environmental Management'</p>
              <p>Now in its tenth year (2017-18) the programme has seen more 
                than <a href="carbonmastersalumni.htm">300 'Carbon Masters'</a> graduate and has this year attracted 
                another great cohort, drawn from all over the world and representing a 
                wealth of experience and different academic backgrounds. Applications 
                for study on the programme for the 2017-18 academic year are still 
                open.</p>
             
              <p>&nbsp;</p>
              <p>The Masters programme is run jointly by the School of Geosciences, 
                School of Economics and Business School at the Universityof Edinburgh 
                . Applications are now being accepted for 2017-2018. Visit the 
                <b><a href="http://www.ed.ac.uk/geosciences/postgraduate/taught-masters/msc-carbon-management">MSc 
                in Carbon Management</a></b> programme webpage for information 
                on how to apply. To view some of our amazing alumni see: .</p>

<p>

